    "summary": "The Pugachev Rebellion (1773–1775 AD) was the largest popular uprising in Russian history before the 1917 revolution — a massive revolt of Cossacks, peasants, serfs, and non-Russian peoples of the Volga and Ural regions led by Yemelyan Pugachev, a Don Cossack who claimed to be the murdered Tsar Peter III. Pugachev's ability to claim a royal identity was crucial to the rebellion's success: in Russian peasant culture, the idea of the 'true tsar' who would free the serfs was a powerful myth, and Pugachev issued decrees promising the abolition of serfdom, cancellation of taxes, distribution of noble lands, and autonomy for Cossack communities. At its peak, the rebellion controlled a vast territory from the Urals to the Volga, including the city of Kazan (briefly), and threatened Moscow itself.\n\nThe rebellion's suppression by [[event:2367|Catherine the Great's]] forces required a major military effort and resulted in tens of thousands of deaths, followed by brutal reprisals. Pugachev was captured in 1774 by his own former allies, transported to Moscow in an iron cage, and executed in January 1775. The rebellion had significant consequences for Russian governance: Catherine, shaken by the demonstration that serfdom could generate violent revolution, paradoxically strengthened noble power over serfs (the Charter of the Nobility, 1785) while also undertaking administrative reforms that reorganized the empire's provinces. Pugachev's rebellion thus helped consolidate the alliance between the autocracy and the nobility that characterized Russian governance for the next century, while confirming for Catherine — and for Russian elites generally — the danger of peasant emancipation without controlled reform.",
